==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -ward
<hw>-ward</hw> <pr>(w⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>,

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ward
<hw>Ward</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>weard</ets>,
fem., guard, <ets>weard</ets>, masc., keeper, guard; akin to OS.
<ets>ward</ets> a watcher, warden, G. <ets>wart</ets>, OHG.
<ets>wart</ets>, Icel. <ets>v⟦oum⟧r⟦edh⟧r</ets> a warden, a watch, Goth.
<ets>-wards</ets> in da⟦uacute⟧ra<ets>wards</ets> a doorkeeper, and E.
<ets>wary</ets>; cf. OF. <ets>warde</ets> guard, from the German. See
<er>Ware</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, <er>Wary</er>, and cf. <er>Guard</er>,
<er>Wraith</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of guarding; watch;
guard; guardianship; specifically, a guarding during the day. See the
Note under <er>Watch</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Still, when she slept, he kept both watch and <qex>ward</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, guards; garrison; defender;
protector; means of guarding; defense; protection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For the best <qex>ward</qex> of mine honor.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The assieged castle's <qex>ward</qex>⟦br⟧
Their steadfast stands did mightily maintain.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For want of other <qex>ward</qex>,⟦br⟧
He lifted up his hand, his front to guard.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The state of being under guard or guardianship;
confinement under guard; the condition of a child under a guardian;
custody.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And he put them in <qex>ward</qex> in the house of the captain of
the guard.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xl. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I must attend his majesty's command, to whom I am now in
<qex>ward</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is also inconvenient, in Ireland, that the <qex>wards</qex> and
marriages of gentlemen's children should be in the disposal of any of
those lords.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A guarding or defensive motion or position, as in
fencing; guard.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Thou knowest my old <xex>ward</xex>; here I
lay, and thus I bore my point.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, is guarded.</def>
Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>A minor or person under the care of a guardian;
<as>as, a <ex>ward</ex> in chancery</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧You know our
father's <xex>ward</xex>, the fair Monimia.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Otway.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A division of a county.</def> <mark>[Eng. &
Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>A division, district, or quarter of a town or
city.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Throughout the trembling city placed a guard,⟦br⟧
Dealing an equal share to every <qex>ward</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>A division of a forest.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>A division of a hospital; <as>as, a fever
<ex>ward</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A projecting ridge of metal in the
interior of a lock, to prevent the use of any key which has not a
corresponding notch for passing it.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A notch or
slit in a key corresponding to a ridge in the lock which it fits; a ward
notch.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lock is made . . . more secure by attaching <qex>wards</qex>
to the front, as well as to the back, plate of the lock, in which case
the key must be furnished with corresponding notches.</q>
<rj><qau>Tomlinson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1627 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ward penny</b></col> <fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd> money
paid to the sheriff or castellan for watching and warding a castle.</cd>
-- <col><b>Ward staff</b></col>, <cd>a constable's or watchman's
staff.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ward</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ward
<hw>Ward</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Warded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Warding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>wardien</ets>, AS.
<ets>weardian</ets> to keep, protect; akin to OS. <ets>ward<?/n</ets> to
watch, take care, OFries. <ets>wardia</ets>, OHG. <ets>wart<?/n</ets>,
G. <ets>warten</ets> to wait, wait on, attend to, Icel.
<ets>var<?/a</ets> to guarantee defend, Sw. <ets>v⟦aring⟧rda</ets> to
guard, to watch; cf. OF. <ets>warder</ets>, of German origin. See
<er>Ward</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Award</er>, <er>Guard</er>,
<er>Reward</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To keep in safety; to watch; to guard; formerly, in
a specific sense, to guard during the day time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose gates he found fast shut, no living wight⟦br⟧
To <qex>ward</qex> the same.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To defend; to protect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tell him it was a hand that <qex>warded</qex> him⟦br⟧
From thousand dangers.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To defend by walls, fortifications, etc.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To fend off; to repel; to turn aside, as anything
mischievous that approaches; -- usually followed by
<xex>off</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>wards</qex> a felling blow, now strikes again.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pointed javelin <qex>warded</qex> off his rage.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It instructs the scholar in the various methods of
<qex>warding</qex> off the force of objections.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ward</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Ward
<hw>Ward</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be vigilant; to keep
guard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act on the defensive with a weapon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She redoubling her blows drove the stranger to no other shift than
to <qex>ward</qex> and go back.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ward-corn</ent>⟦br⟧
